<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>NOTE: THIS POST WAS MADE BEFORE THE RELEASE OF PoP.  SPELL STATS DISCUSSED BELOW ARE VERY DIFFERENT THAN WHAT WENT LIVE!</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
<br>
--------- ORIGINAL MESSAGE -------------<br>
<br>
With the impending nerf/fix to mod rods, I decided to examine the damage contribution of magicians vs 2 other classes -- druids and wizards -- across each era of EQ.  <br>
<br>
Before I get into the analysis, please allow me to stipulate a few things:<br>
<br>
1) I do not wish to debate the change to mod rods.  There are other threads for it.<br>
2) I chose these two classes and these two classes only.  If you want to compare other classes, feel free.<br>
3) I compare ONLY straight spell damage.  I do not factor in critical spells (an innate wizard ability), resist mods (wizards and druids have them) on damage spells or AA.  These things only strengthen the final conclusion anyway...they don't contradict it.<br>
4) For the purpose of this analysis only DD/Bolt spells were compared.  DOTs were ignored.  (They really wouldn't change the picture for these classes anyway).<br>
5) Finally -- and perhaps most importantly, I am not advocating a nerf to any class!<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong> The Issue</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
<br>
The issue as I see it is that any given class can only contribute two things to a group or large scale raid:<br>
<br>
1) Direct damage - damage the desired mob<br>
2) Indirect damage - enhance the group/raid's abilities or inhibit the mob's abilities<br>
<br>
It is my belief that balance means that classes should provide SIMILAR levels of value in these two areas.  <br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong> The Metrics</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
<br>
Direct damage is the easiest to measure.  I use the following metrics in measuring spell damage:<br>
<br>
fcDPS = First Cast DPS = max damage / casting time<br>
ccDPS = Chain Cast DPS = max damage / (casting time + hold time)<br>
MDM = Mana Dmg Multipler = max damage / mana cost<br>
<br>
fcDPS is an indication of how quickly initial damage can be delivered while ccDPS factors the hold time into the calculation.  MDM gives a general sense for how efficiently the spell is converting mana to damage.  Together, these three measures provide a fair basis for comparing these 3 classes.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong> The Comparison</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
<br>
For the purpose of comparison, I was interested in looking at only the highest level in each era of EverQuest.  Further, I was interested in expressing each classes metrics both in terms of a wizard -- a wizard is 100% of a wizard whereas a magician is x%? of a wizard.  Finally, I wanted to see how these metrics had changed with the previous eras as well as with the soon-to-be-released Planes of Power.<br>
<br>
Without further ado, here is the result (and the reason this thread is a bit wide):<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE IMAGE START--><img src="http://www.ballio.com/eracompare.gif"/><!--EZCODE IMAGE END--><br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong> Observations</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
<br>
1) The power of a magician to deal spell damage, relative to that of a wizard has fallen from the original game.<br>
2) The relative spell damage of a magician is currently slated to take it's biggest drop yet in PoP.<br>
3) The difference in ccDPS between a magician and wizard is well beyond what a magician epic pet can deliver in DPS.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong> Conclusions</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
<br>
1) Given my concept that class contribution is limited to (Direct + Indirect Damage), since our Direct power is falling, our pet's DPS or our Indirect value needs to rise to compensate and lkeep the class in balance.<br>
<br>
2) The DPS descrepency is too great to be made up by a pet.  Pets would clearly be just too powerful.  Note that the DPS damage gap in PoP is currently more than 300 DPS!<br>
<br>
3) Magician indirect value cannot drop without hurting the class significantly.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong> Final Word</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
<br>
Go ahead and nerf the rod.  But give magicians something REAL and SUSTAINABLE in terms of an indirect contribution to a group and raid.  Summoned trinkets that quickly get replaced by &quot;real&quot; loot is not a sustainable indirect contribution.<br>
<br>
Revisit mage spell DPS.  And revisit pets in raid situations.<br>
<br>
And finally, it's not analyzed above, but other classes have mana regen spells -- they can Lich, Canni, Harvest -- or steal mana!  If you make the rod give back less mana than it requires, you will leave magicians with no way to transverge for their own regen.  We only have Transons' Phantasmal Protection today -- all other caster classes have higher mana regen thanks to the aforementioned spells.  We a need better mana regen PRE-PoP. <p><table border="0"><tr>
